{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522567"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:46:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:46:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13839"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13839"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.02,0.02,0.71,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54207"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13839"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39683"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1132"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"3535"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16013"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54207"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of worsening left hip pain. He reports no trauma or injury. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his vital signs are within normal limits. There is tenderness on palpation of the left hip and a slight limp when walking. An image of the patient\u0027s lower limbs are shown below. X-rays of the pelvis reveal areas of sclerosis and lytic lesions in the left iliac bone. Blood tests show elevated serum alkaline phosphatase of 450 U/L (40-130).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osteosarcoma","Atypical femoral fracture","Osteoporosis","Paget\u0027s disease of bone","Osteomalacia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and investigation findings in this case are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease of bone\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterised by osteoclast abnormalities, leading to increased bone turnover and abnormal remodelling, resulting in bone deformity and pain. The patient\u0027s age, localised pain, image demonstrating bowing, and radiographic findings of mixed lytic and sclerotic lesions are typical of Paget\u0027s disease. The markedly elevated serum alkaline phosphatase is a key biochemical marker for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaget\u0027s disease of bone typically affects older adults, with a peak incidence in those over 50 years of age. It can involve a single bone (monostotic) or multiple bones (polyostotic), with the pelvis, spine, skull, and long bones being commonly affected sites. The disease progresses through three stages: lytic (increased bone resorption), mixed lytic and blastic (increased bone formation), and sclerotic (dense but structurally weak bone). Complications can include bone pain, deformity, fractures, and rarely, osteosarcoma. Treatment often involves bisphosphonates to reduce bone turnover and manage symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with severe pain and swelling, often in younger patients. While it can occur in older adults, especially as a complication of Paget\u0027s disease of bone, the gradual onset and radiographic findings are less consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoporosis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by decreased bone density but does not typically cause the mixed lytic and sclerotic lesions seen in this case. Additionally, osteoporosis alone would not explain the elevated alkaline phosphatase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtypical femoral fractures\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with long-term bisphosphonate use and present with acute pain. This patient has no history of bisphosphonate use, and the gradual onset of symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteomalacia\u003C/strong\u003E results from vitamin D deficiency or impaired metabolism, leading to inadequate bone mineralisation. While it can cause bone pain, the radiographic findings and elevated alkaline phosphatase are more consistent with Paget\u0027s disease of bone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paget\u0027s disease of bone is characterised by increased bone turnover, leading to bone deformity and pain.","Elevated serum alkaline phosphatase is a key biochemical marker for Paget\u0027s disease of bone.","Paget\u0027s disease of bone typically affects older adults and can involve single or multiple bones."],"references":["Britton C, Walsh J. Paget disease of bone. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Mar;41:100-3. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/march/paget-disease-of-bone"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39683"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13839"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20787"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20787"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xfS4IwB6kvhEOyuLXLEGBqBuuouIS3.jpg","t